TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Effects of Different Organizational Environments Upon Decisions About Organizational Structure
AU  - Bourgeois, L. J.
AU  - McAllister, Daniel W.
AU  - Mitchell, Terence R.
Y1  - 1978/09/01
PY  - 1978
DA  - 1978/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255732
DO  - 10.5465/255732
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 508
EP  - 514
VL  - 21
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article examines the effects of different organizational environments on decisions about organizational structure. Much of the organization theory literature concentrates on defining which organizational structures and management styles are most fit for different technologies and/or environmental contingencies. Managers may address increased environmental pressure by an increase in structure, possibly followed by a relaxation of controls once the danger has subsided. The reasoning is that turbulence causes uncertainty or stress which leads to attempts to reduce that uncertainty or stress by structuring the organizational setting.
AB  - The article examines the effects of different organizational environments on decisions about organizational structure. Much of the organization theory literature concentrates on defining which organizational structures and management styles are most fit for different technologies and/or environmental contingencies. Managers may address increased environmental pressure by an increase in structure, possibly followed by a relaxation of controls once the danger has subsided. The reasoning is that turbulence causes uncertainty or stress which leads to attempts to reduce that uncertainty or stress by structuring the organizational setting.
